    icon: "fa-pen-nib",
    shortDesc: "From ancient Sumerian clay tablets to alphabets — how writing transformed civilization.",
    leftPage: "Writing is one of the most important inventions in human history. Before writing existed, all knowledge had to be memorized and passed down orally. The earliest known writing system was invented by the Sumerians in Mesopotamia — the region that is now modern Iraq — around 3,400 BCE. They used sharp sticks to press wedge-shaped marks into clay tablets. This system was called cuneiform and was used mainly to record business transactions and food supplies.",
    rightPage: "The Phoenicians, a trading people from the Mediterranean coast, created the first true alphabet around 1050 BCE. Unlike cuneiform, which had hundreds of symbols, the Phoenician alphabet had only 22 letters. It was easy to learn and spread rapidly through trade networks. Our modern English alphabet is directly descended from the Phoenician alphabet through Greek and Latin. The invention of the printing press by Johannes Gutenberg in 1440 made books affordable for ordinary people for the first time.",
